Exploratory analysis of C2D data

Objectives

This file contains an exploratory analysis of the c2d dataset with a view to probing its usefulness for our research. There are at least two ways in which the c2d data can enrich our current work.

  1. Identify critical referendum cases: One of the LIDD objectives is to map the limits of DD in terms of the clash between popular sovereignty and the rule of law (esp. broader limits set by norms of international law). Therefore, it is of interest to identify the scale of the potential clash and this can be done by examining all referendums. As a cut-off point we choose the year 1990 across the C.o.E states. It is a symbolic date that marks the democratization wave of post-Soviet successor states and CEEC states belonging to the C.oE. How many potential instances are we dealing with? What was the outcome in these cases?

  2. Enrich the data app: It would be good to enrich the current data APP with referendum event data. Data regarding referendum events that can be linked to our working LIDD typology is of particular value. Evidently, it will be impossible to find third-party datasets that exactly map onto the LIDD typology since our typology is new and hopefully goes beyond what is already out there. Nonetheless, enrichment is certainly possible.

Summary

My basic conclusion is that the c2d can partly address the two objectives above, especially (2). We can quite easily enrich the app with more data that maps onto a simpler 3-fold LIDD typology with little effort.

The c2d data also offers some valuable shortcuts for identifying LIDD critical cases, point (1) above. It is not perfect in this regard, and some extra work will be required on our part. Elements of that work are unavoidable. We need a LIDD typology of what I would call critical LIDD cases, i.e., those types of cases that bring to the fore the potential clash between popular sovereignty and the rule of law. How can we identify such referendum events? The good news is that I think the c2d coding of referendum events can help quite a lot in this regard. But we will need to go a bit further if we want an operational LIDD typology of critical cases.

The data

The c2d dataset was manually downloaded from the website (there is somewhat annoyingly no coherent aggregated datafile). The following filters were applied:

  1. Only C.oE. member states
  2. Only national level referendums
  3. Only referendums since 2000

The total count of referendums is 729. However, most of these referendums are from Switzerland, which has had 282 during this time period. Switzerland accounts for over one-third of the data. The rest of the referendums. Overall, the median number of referendums held over the last twenty-years by C.o.E member states is 5.

Excluding Switzerland’s 282 referendums the distribution looks like this.

The count of referendums actually appears to be quite stable over the past 30 years (excluding Siwtzerland). The almost 450 referendums are relatively evenly spread at around 150 each decade, as shown in the second graph below.

There is, however, some double counting in the data. For instance, the UK has had 2 referendums, one on changing the electoral system and the other case being the Brexit referendum. However, because C2D dichotomizes the vote into a YES/NO they transform the Brexit vote option into two votes: Remain (YES versus NO) and Leave (Yes versus NO). Another case is Cyprus, while the Republic of Cyprus has had one vote on the Anan reunification plan, the occupied Northern part has also had two votes. There could be others, for instance a multi-option referendum, say with options A, B or C would get transformed into 3 yes/no votes.

To get a fair picture of the distribution it’s a good idea to take out some of the outliers. I’d leave out Switzerland and Azerbaijan for now. In the case of Azerbaijan, it has only had 6 referendum events. The latest one on a 2016 constitutional reform included 29 questions, i.e., separate constitutional amendments. To avoid distortions to the analysis, I’ll put these two special cases in the annex.

With our two special cases exclusion, the total count of referendums is 378. The median count of referendums remains the same 5 (which shows why it’s a good metric to use).

Apart from all the normal variables one would expect, e.g. vote result, turnout, referendum question, yes vote, no vote etc., the C2D database has some useful extra variables that could help us avoid a lot of time-consuming rounds of coding. There are 3 that I would single out. Unfortunately, they don’t have a codebook where the variables are defined precisely. Nonetheless, it’s easy to tell what they refer to. They are called:

  • institution: This refers to the particular institution or instrument of direct democracy, what they call: citizen’s initiative, governmental referendum, mandatory referendum, optional referendum and counter proposal.
  • vote_trigger: Three seemingly self-explanatory categories are provided: Automatic, Bottom-up and Top-down.
  • vote_trigger_actor: This category includes actors such as Government, Parliament, Constitution and some others.
  • hierarchy_legal_norm: This category includes Constitution, Laws, Ordinances, Treaties etc., though there seem to be lots of missing categories.

Referendum topic

The c2d data has a very useful extra variable, which is called a tag. It is essentially a coding of the referendum topic, basically what type of policy issue the vote was on. They provide up to 3 tags for a given referendum. I have split these into tagA, tagB and tagC.

The tags operate at different levels of granularity. So, tagA is the highest level and tagC the most detailed level.

We can take a random sample of 10 referendums to explore this coding system.
